      {
        "id": 260873,
        "name": "Trevor Kafka",
        "username": "trevorkafka",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/trevorkafka/{size}/50678_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-02-09T23:24:19.437Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I tried to make another feature request about LaTeX equation support for Signal, but it was shut down as a duplicate of this request. Since three years have passed, I feel personally that this is quite harsh, but nothing I can do about that.</p>\n<p>I do feel the benefits for the STEM community worldwide, for both professionals and students, would be absolutely massive. <strong>Currently, mathematics is the only widely-used (and globally-universal) language that I am aware of that is not supported by any major or semi-major instant messaging system.</strong></p>\n<p>Here‚Äôs the text of my original post since it was taken down:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I know this might be a long shot since no major messaging apps currently support it, but I‚Äôd love to see LaTeX support added to Signal. Math and science communication often relies on equations to express ideas clearly, yet messaging platforms consistently overlook this need. As a result, students, educators, researchers, and professionals in these fields are left with clunky workarounds like images, ASCII approximations, or external tools‚Äînone of which are ideal for quick, seamless discussions.</p>\n<p>Imagine being able to type something like $\\frac{a}{b}$ and having it render properly as a fraction within Signal, powered by something like MathJax. This would be a game-changer for math and science communities, making Signal a uniquely valuable tool for education and collaboration. No comparable messaging app offers this natively, so implementing it would set Signal apart as the go-to choice for technical discussions.</p>\n<p>I know development resources are always limited, but if there‚Äôs any way to make this happen‚Äîwhether as an optional feature or within specific group chats‚Äîit would be a huge step forward for those of us who rely on equations to communicate effectively.</p>\n<p>Would anyone else find this useful?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote group-volunteer_moderators\" data-username=\"Leptopoda\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"40878\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/leptopoda/48/5476_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Leptopoda:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Also latex is really slow</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Pre-rendered content (e.g. - via an image) is many times slower than LaTeX rendering (both in generating/uploading as well as downloading). It also lacks the ability to be inserted inline with text in a message (think about howw emojis can be inserted in the middle of a sentence).</p>\n<aside class=\"quote group-volunteer_moderators\" data-username=\"Leptopoda\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"40878\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/leptopoda/48/5476_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Leptopoda:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Also latex supports a lot of libraries of wich most used and publicly available are bundled in the texlive project.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>While LaTeX does support a wide variety of libraries, only basic functionality, such as those supported by the default distribution of MathJax, would be more than sufficient to have an incredible amount of impact.</p>",
        "post_number": 9,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 10,
        "updated_at": "2025-02-09T23:39:29.259Z",
